@gianm which functionality you are asking about ?
 Considering null as null yes that is what it is set to by default.
 DoubleSketches/quantiles am not aware of any usage or actual testing

@jon-wei added some of this stuff to the docs in #7407.

Btw, if you are doing a cardinality count without grouping by anything, the memory requirements are probably irrelevant. Either one is small enough that without the need to create a lot of them, the memory use is trivial.

I'm not sure if folks with more experience will be able to chime in, but if not then you might need to determine some of these answers yourself through performance testing.

@egor-ryashin @gianm ok. Could you please suggest criteria for how to choose between INFO and DEBUG?

@gianm I still disagree, however, with the suggestion about TRACE. Regarding memory allocations, it should be possible to profile them much more effectively using [async-profiler in allocation mode](https://github.com/jvm-profiling-tools/async-profiler#allocation-profiling). Tracing each and every HTTP request/response should be enabled by some Jetty flag, or if Jetty doesn't have such, by a special Druid's flag because while you want to debug each and every HTTP request and response, you probably don't want to trace, for example, each and every [insert other type of very noisy thing here], and vice versa. TRACE is so noisy that use cases should be specialized. So I think it should rather be
```
if (specialFlagIsOn) {
  log.info()
}
```

Than `log.trace()`.
